nt Andrew's Church, Thursby, Allerdale district, Cumberland, England":"Thursby, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","Crofton Manor, Thursby, Allerdale district, Cumberland, England":"Thursby, Cumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Crofton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Crofton, for example in Cumbria, Greater London (formerly in Kent), Hampshire, Lincolnshire, Wiltshire, and Yorkshire. Most of these are named from Old English <i>croft</i> ‘paddock, vegetable garden’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, but the one in Greater London probably has as its first element Old English <i>cropp</i> ‘swelling, mound’ (compare   Cropper  ) and that in Lincolnshire Old English <i>croh</i> ‘saffron’ (from Latin <i>crocus</i>).","History: A family called Crofton was established in Ireland by John Crofton (died 1610), who held high office under Elizabeth I and acquired vast estates when he accompanied Sir Henry Sidney, Lord Deputy, into Ireland in 1565."],"variants":[{"name":"Cropper","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): occupational name for a picker of fruit or vegetables or a reaper of cereal crops, from <i>cropper(e)</i> ‘one who reaps crops or trims trees’, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>cropt(en)</i> ‘to pick’. The word was used also to denote the polling of livestock and the name may therefore have been given to someone with this responsibility."]}]},{"name":"Clement","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Late Latin name <i>Clemens</i> (genitive <i>Clementis</i>) meaning ‘merciful’. This was borne by several early saints, notably the fourth pope and the early Christian theologian Clement of Alexandria (Titus Flavius Clemens,   ad  ?150–?215 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":19,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":50,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Clement de Crofton was born in 1240, in Thursby, Cumberland, England, his father, John de Crofton, was 24 and his mother, Ada de Dundraw, was 23. He married Johanna de Ulnesby in 1266, in Thursby, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1299, in his hometown, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1240–1299":"1240–1299","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1277–1345":"1277–1345","1216–Male":"1216–Surnud","1218–Female":"1218–Surnud","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1345":"1345","1245":"1245","1266":"1266","1277":"1277","1299":"1299","1240":"1240","1290":"1290","1218":"1218","Saint Andrew's Church, Thursby, Allerdale district, Cumberland, England":"Thursby, Cumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",